Descriptor.0: EPD-STEP-MAIN>Energetic Particle Detector, SupraThermal Electrons and Protons, Main product

PI_affiliation.0: Space Research Group, Universidad de Alcala

TEXT.0: Energetic Particle Detector (EPD). Instrument suite, part of the scientific payload aboard the Solar Orbiter mission, dedicated to the study of solar energetic particles. EPD measures electrons, protons and heavy ions with high temporal resolution over a wide energy range, from suprathermal energies to several hundreds of MeV/nucleon. It is composed of four units: SupraThermal Electrons and Protons (STEP), Electron Proton Telescope (EPT), Suprathermal Ion Spectrograph (SIS) and High Energy Telescope (HET).

Count rate in the background pixel (0) for the integral channel

VarAttributes.VAR_NOTES: Count rate measured by the background pixel (0) on the integral channel. This pixel is shielded to prevent particles from the nominal field of view from reaching the detector, but it is still susceptible to highly energetic particles penetrating the housing and passive parts of the sensor. It can be used to get a rough estimation of the background signal in the other pixels, which are currently not corrected for this effect

Conversion factors for computing electron intensities from integral-magnet flux excess for pixel 1

VarAttributes.VAR_NOTES: Electron intensity in pixel 1 can be obtained as Electron_Flux_01_Mult *  ( Integral_01_Flux - Magnet_Flux_01 ). The result gives the intensities in the energy channels given in the variables Electron_Bins_*. This factor is calculated as the ratio between  the product of the geometric factor and the bin width for protons and those for electrons. During periods with poor electron count statistics, this operation may lead to negative values. Although negative intensities have no physical meaning by themselves, they should be used when performing time or energy averages in order to get the correct results.
